02:44.900 --> 02:46.600
     Afternoon, everybody.      

02:46.700 --> 02:49.500
                    WOODY:      
                    Norm!       

02:49.600 --> 02:51.300
Well, that was it, Woody.       

02:51.300 --> 02:53.500
 Last chance; I'm out of here.  

02:53.500 --> 02:54.800
                 You caught them
                 by surprise.   

02:54.800 --> 02:56.400
                I'm telling you,
                they'll get it. 

02:56.400 --> 02:58.600
Woody, new crowd's              
a bunch of stiffs, okay?        

02:58.700 --> 03:00.200
They're never going             
to get it.                      

03:02.300 --> 03:04.600
          Hey, Woody.           

03:04.700 --> 03:06.400
          Hey, Eddie.           

03:06.400 --> 03:07.600
( <i>chuckling</i> ):                  
How you doing?                  

03:07.700 --> 03:09.200
        Good, how are you?      
Good. You know,                 

03:09.200 --> 03:10.800
I passed Norm Peterson          
on the stairs.                  

03:10.800 --> 03:12.300
He didn't give me               
the time of day.                

03:12.300 --> 03:14.400
                  Oh, it's 3:15.

03:14.400 --> 03:16.700
        Thanks.                 

03:16.800 --> 03:17.700
Well, would you like a drink,   

03:17.700 --> 03:19.200
        or did you just         
        drop in for the time?   

03:19.200 --> 03:20.300
Now that you mentioned it.      

03:20.400 --> 03:21.500
Say, is, uh, Carla around?      

03:21.600 --> 03:23.100
            She said            
she wanted to talk to me.       

03:23.100 --> 03:24.500
Said it was real important, eh? 

03:24.600 --> 03:25.500
    She just went upstairs.     

03:25.600 --> 03:27.100
      She'll be back down       
          in a minute.          

03:27.100 --> 03:28.200
EDDIE:                          
Good.                           

03:28.200 --> 03:30.100
        Well, we haven't seen   
        you for a while, eh?    

03:30.100 --> 03:32.300
  Yeah, you know, Carla and I   
     kind of drifted apart.     

03:32.400 --> 03:34.400
         I don't know,          
 I haven't seen her in months.  

03:34.400 --> 03:36.000
                    The usual?  
    You bet, Woody.             

03:36.100 --> 03:37.100
          Good memory.          

03:37.200 --> 03:38.400
            Thanks.             

03:38.500 --> 03:39.900
      What is your usual?       

03:39.900 --> 03:42.300
    Uh, just give me a beer.    

03:42.400 --> 03:44.000
                Coming right up.
Sam around?                     

03:44.000 --> 03:45.400
            Oh, didn't you hear?
    No.                         

03:45.400 --> 03:47.800
        Sam sold the bar to     
        some big corporation.   

03:47.800 --> 03:49.000
                  Bought a boat.

03:49.000 --> 03:51.300
             He's sailing around
             the world with it. 

03:51.300 --> 03:52.400
    Hey, well, good for Sam.    

03:52.400 --> 03:54.100
    Thought he was supposed     
        to get married.         

03:54.100 --> 03:55.400
             Well, Miss Chambers

03:55.400 --> 03:56.500
  went off to write her book,   

03:56.600 --> 03:58.000
only that didn't work out,      

03:58.000 --> 04:00.200
    and last we heard,          
    she was out in Hollywood    

04:00.300 --> 04:01.500
    trying to write for TV.     

04:05.400 --> 04:06.900
              I'll bet whatever 
              she comes up with,

04:06.900 --> 04:08.000
                 it'll be pretty
                 darn good.     

04:08.000 --> 04:09.000
( <i>chuckling</i> )                   

04:09.100 --> 04:10.100
I bet it will.                  

04:12.900 --> 04:14.900
                Oh, Eddie?      

04:16.200 --> 04:17.500
          Hey, Carla.           

04:18.700 --> 04:21.000
    What did you want           
      to talk to me about?      

04:26.400 --> 04:29.400
Okay, see ya.                   

04:29.400 --> 04:31.600
            Yeah, see ya, Eddie.

04:31.600 --> 04:33.500
                      FRASIER:  
                      So, Carla,

04:33.600 --> 04:35.700
    what did Eddie say          
about his impending fatherhood? 

04:35.800 --> 04:38.000
He wants                        
to think about it.              

04:38.000 --> 04:39.400
                    Mmm.        

04:39.400 --> 04:40.700
                  Well, my guess
                  is he'll do   

04:40.800 --> 04:43.400
         exactly what I or any  
         normal, red-blooded men

04:43.400 --> 04:44.900
                 would do in    
                 this situation.

04:45.000 --> 04:46.100
              On the other hand,

04:46.200 --> 04:48.000
            you might actually  
            hear from him again.

04:49.200 --> 04:51.200
  No, I'm joking, I'm joking.   

04:51.200 --> 04:54.500
 Come on, am I the only cut-up  
      left in this morgue?      

04:54.500 --> 04:55.900
                        FRASIER:
                        Come on!

04:56.000 --> 05:00.000
        Remember the old days   
        when things were fun?   

05:00.000 --> 05:02.300
  Do you remember when the bar  
was brimming with scamps,       

05:02.400 --> 05:03.400
    and atop every barstool     

05:03.500 --> 05:05.300
    perched an irrepressible    
         Merry-Andrew?          

05:05.400 --> 05:06.500
    You remember that, Sam?     

05:06.500 --> 05:08.300
( <i>alarmed screech</i> )             

05:08.300 --> 05:10.600
        Oh, my God, Sam!        
                            Sam!

05:10.700 --> 05:11.500
    Sam, you're back!           

05:11.700 --> 05:13.500
                Ah, yeah, you   
                bet I'm back.   

05:13.500 --> 05:14.600
     Oh, look at... Woody!      

05:14.600 --> 05:16.600
         ( <i>chuckling</i> ):         
    Hey, man, how are you?!     

05:16.700 --> 05:18.300
                    Good.       
    Whoo! Look at this.         

05:18.300 --> 05:20.900
                 Hey, everybody.

05:20.900 --> 05:22.500
     Who are these people?      

05:24.100 --> 05:26.300
  Things just aren't the same   
         anymore, Sam.          

05:26.300 --> 05:27.400
Boy, yeah, I'll say.            

05:27.400 --> 05:30.000
Can't believe the number        
of changes around here.         

05:30.100 --> 05:31.600
Thank God                       
you're still pregnant, huh?     

05:31.600 --> 05:32.600
                ( <i>laughing</i> ):   
                Yeah.           

05:32.700 --> 05:33.700
( <i>chuckling</i> )                   

05:33.800 --> 05:35.200
Who's the lucky guy?            

05:35.200 --> 05:36.800
Everybody but Eddie LeBec.      

05:36.800 --> 05:38.400
        Eddie.                  

05:38.400 --> 05:39.900
    Yeah. You thirsty?          
    I'll get you a seltzer.     

05:39.900 --> 05:41.400
Yeah, get me                    
something to drink here.        

05:41.400 --> 05:42.400
              Sam, what happened

05:42.400 --> 05:44.000
 to your around-the-world sail? 

05:44.000 --> 05:45.700
     Well, it kind of lost      
some of its appeal, Woody,      

05:45.800 --> 05:46.700
         after I sank.          

05:46.800 --> 05:48.400
              ALL:              
          Sank? Where?          

05:48.400 --> 05:50.000
  Somewhere in the Caribbean.   

05:50.100 --> 05:51.600
Well, you must                  
feel terrible.                  

05:51.600 --> 05:52.600
     Well, no, not really.      

05:52.600 --> 05:54.200
        You know,               
 a lot of good came out of it.  

05:54.200 --> 05:55.100
I discovered a reef             

05:55.100 --> 05:56.600
that nobody                     
had ever heard of,              

05:56.600 --> 05:58.400
  and even named it after me.   

05:58.500 --> 05:59.800
    "No Brains Atoll."          

05:59.800 --> 06:00.900
          ( <i>laughter</i> )          

06:01.000 --> 06:03.800
( <i>Woody joins in</i> )              

06:03.800 --> 06:05.200
         Maybe you two          
should start calling each other 

06:05.200 --> 06:06.400
        in the morning.         

06:09.700 --> 06:11.700
                          Sammy,

06:11.800 --> 06:13.300
                 it's part of   
                 the new regime.

06:13.300 --> 06:16.200
      They're running this joint
      like a military outfit.   

06:16.200 --> 06:17.800
     Well, that's too bad.      

06:17.800 --> 06:18.900
Oh, no,                         
look at that.                   

06:18.900 --> 06:20.200
What happened                   
to my photograph?               

06:20.300 --> 06:21.500
          Never mind;           
        now you're back,        

06:21.500 --> 06:22.600
                you can buy     
                back the bar,   

06:22.600 --> 06:24.000
              things can be     
              the way they were.

06:24.000 --> 06:26.700
I don't have enough money       
to buy back an ice cube.        

06:26.800 --> 06:29.600
But anyway, you know, hey,      
I just want to work here.       

06:29.600 --> 06:30.800
                    If I can't  
                    be the boss,

06:30.800 --> 06:33.000
          I can at least be the 
          highest-paid employee.

06:33.100 --> 06:34.400
Yeah, well, I don't know.       

06:34.400 --> 06:36.200
We got two bartenders           
already, Sam.                   

06:36.200 --> 06:37.200
            You're kidding. Who?

06:37.300 --> 06:38.600
Well, hold onto                 
your sides.                     

06:38.700 --> 06:41.000
I'm going to introduce you      
to Mr. Chucklepuss.             

06:41.100 --> 06:42.200
                Hey, Wayne.     

06:42.300 --> 06:43.800
Sam...                          

06:43.800 --> 06:45.400
         this is Wayne;         
    Wayne, Sam Malone.          

06:45.500 --> 06:47.100
    How do you do?              
                    Hello.      

06:47.100 --> 06:49.600
 Sorry, Wayne, but Sam is going 
     to take over your job.     

06:49.700 --> 06:51.000
Yeah, well,                     
there's no reason               

06:51.100 --> 06:52.900
why you can't hang around       

06:53.000 --> 06:54.700
and be a relief bartender.      

06:54.700 --> 06:57.000
            I'm hardly a        
            relief bartender.   

06:57.100 --> 06:58.100
      Yeah, that's right.       

06:58.200 --> 06:59.300
             You know, uh, Wayne

06:59.300 --> 07:01.100
              has bored the hell
              out of people     

07:01.100 --> 07:04.200
      in some of the finest bars
      and restaurants in Boston.

07:04.200 --> 07:06.600
          And as he'd be the    
          first one to tell you,

07:06.600 --> 07:08.700
             he can make any    
             drink known to man.

07:08.800 --> 07:10.100
Oh, is that right?              

07:10.100 --> 07:11.700
Try me.                         
            Okay.               

07:11.800 --> 07:13.000
        Um, a moonbeam.         

07:13.000 --> 07:14.100
With or without                 
curaçao?                        

07:14.200 --> 07:15.400
              Serendipity, neat.

07:15.400 --> 07:16.200
That only comes with ice.       

07:16.300 --> 07:17.600
                Saddleback.     
Onion or olive?                 

07:17.700 --> 07:19.300
            Both. Stick 'em     
            in your nostrils.   

07:19.400 --> 07:20.500
                ( <i>chuckles</i> )    

07:25.700 --> 07:27.100
    Well, that's all right.     

07:27.100 --> 07:29.500
             What the hell, I'll
             just come at this  
             from another angle.

07:29.600 --> 07:31.400
         Uh, who's, uh,         
  who's running the show now?   

07:31.400 --> 07:33.600
    Oh, no, no, I-I wouldn't    
     approach it that way.      

07:33.600 --> 07:36.800
No, this new manager            
eats live sharks for breakfast. 

07:36.800 --> 07:38.300
Ah, but don't go by me.         

07:38.400 --> 07:40.600
I've hated every boss           
I've ever had.                  

07:40.700 --> 07:42.000
        How can you say that?   

07:42.100 --> 07:43.100
                I was your boss.

07:43.100 --> 07:44.200
    Yeah, right.                

07:44.300 --> 07:46.000
             Oh, I was; come on.

07:46.000 --> 07:47.800
Anyway,                         
I really hate her.              

07:47.800 --> 07:50.100
     "Her"? Whoa-- a woman?     

07:50.200 --> 07:52.200
      Oh, is she married?       

07:52.200 --> 07:53.300
Who'd marry her?                

07:53.300 --> 07:54.600
      An unmarried woman.       

07:54.600 --> 07:57.400
     Might take me all of five  
     minutes to get my job back.

07:57.500 --> 07:58.700
    Ha-ha-ha.                   

07:58.700 --> 08:00.100
                      Why? What?

08:00.100 --> 08:02.100
Oh, no, what, is she            
one of those pasty-faced        

08:02.100 --> 08:04.300
little business school          
graduates with thick glasses    

08:04.400 --> 08:05.800
and her hair pulled back        
so tight                        

08:05.800 --> 08:07.700
she hears through her eyes--    
one of those?                   

08:07.700 --> 08:09.000
         She's coming right now.

08:09.100 --> 08:10.800
                Why don't you be

08:10.900 --> 08:11.500
              the judge of that?

08:11.500 --> 08:12.700
    Watch this.                 

08:12.700 --> 08:14.600
        I came up               
    with a few new grabbers     

08:14.700 --> 08:17.400
    while I was out at sea.     

08:19.000 --> 08:21.400
        Mm-boo-ah.              

08:30.700 --> 08:32.799
    Miss Rebecca Howe,          
          Sam Malone.           

08:32.900 --> 08:34.400
    Sam, Rebecca Howe.          

08:34.400 --> 08:35.700
How do you do?                  

08:35.700 --> 08:37.600
        Ah-voo-ah.              

08:39.200 --> 08:40.700
    And to you.                 

08:40.799 --> 08:42.799
If you'll excuse me.            

08:45.800 --> 08:47.000
    Boy, you know,              

08:47.000 --> 08:48.700
she's almost as great-looking   
as I am.                        

08:48.700 --> 08:50.800
CARLA:                          
Almost.                         

08:50.900 --> 08:53.500
Gee, I wonder what              
she'll make me for breakfast?   

08:56.700 --> 08:57.800
         Miss Tortelli, you have

08:57.800 --> 08:59.200
        a couple of customers   
        in the corner           

08:59.200 --> 09:01.300
    that look like they're on   
    the verge of a good time.   

09:01.300 --> 09:04.000
  You better hurry over there   
 and put your usual stop to it. 

09:04.000 --> 09:05.700
Yes, ma'am.                     

09:11.500 --> 09:14.000
                 Good afternoon,
                 Miss Howe.     

09:14.000 --> 09:15.100
    Hello, Woody.               

09:15.100 --> 09:16.700
         I mean Wayne.          

09:16.700 --> 09:19.600
          Did you lose          
      your name tag again?      

09:19.700 --> 09:20.900
                        Yeah.   

09:21.000 --> 09:23.200
        But I found my pants.   

09:26.000 --> 09:28.100
Keep up the good work,          
Woody.                          

09:28.100 --> 09:29.800
Uh, excuse me.                  

09:29.900 --> 09:31.200
Um, I want to apologize         

09:31.300 --> 09:32.800
for my behavior                 
back there.                     

09:32.800 --> 09:34.100
    I was led astray.           

09:34.200 --> 09:38.200
Somebody told me that you were  
kind of a schnauzer.            

09:38.300 --> 09:40.600
                Uh-- Sam Malone.

09:40.600 --> 09:42.400
        Yes. Yes.               
            You're the gentleman

09:42.400 --> 09:43.900
                that used to    
                own this bar.   

09:43.900 --> 09:46.000
    Well, I heard you were      
    sailing around the world.   

09:46.000 --> 09:47.600
Well, I was going               
to do that, but, uh,            

09:47.600 --> 09:49.500
something                       
kept pulling me back here,      

09:49.500 --> 09:52.300
and I just couldn't figure out  
what it was, till now.          

09:52.300 --> 09:54.800
              Which reminds me  
              of the other thing
              I heard about you.

09:54.800 --> 09:56.900
( <i>chuckling</i> ):                  
Oh, no...                       

09:56.900 --> 09:58.600
        Wait, let me set        
the record straight here.       

09:58.700 --> 10:00.300
        There have been         
      a lot of ridiculous,      

10:00.400 --> 10:03.200
unbelievable rumors             
about my sexual prowess.        

10:03.200 --> 10:05.800
    I just want to tell you     
    that most of them           

10:05.800 --> 10:07.400
    are right on the money.     

10:07.400 --> 10:08.800
     You know, Mr. Malone,      

10:08.800 --> 10:11.300
     we've known each other     
         only seconds,          

10:11.300 --> 10:13.400
 and I'm already tired of you.  

10:14.500 --> 10:15.900
Uh, w-w-wait                    
a minute,                       

10:15.900 --> 10:17.300
         wait a minute.         

10:17.300 --> 10:18.400
I know                          
you think you've had            

10:18.400 --> 10:20.600
  just about enough excitement  
          for one day,          

10:20.700 --> 10:22.000
    but there's more.           

10:22.000 --> 10:25.200
I'm back... and I'm ready       
to jump behind the bar.         

10:25.300 --> 10:27.400
            We're fully staffed,
            Mr. Malone.         

10:27.400 --> 10:28.800
            Jump somewhere else.

10:28.800 --> 10:30.300
  Uh, well, hold on a second.   

10:30.300 --> 10:32.800
Can't we, uh,                   
can't we discuss this?          

10:32.800 --> 10:34.100
                We just did.    

10:34.100 --> 10:36.100
No, no, no,                     
I meant someplace private       

10:36.200 --> 10:38.300
where we could                  
slip out of our things          

10:38.300 --> 10:40.500
and say howdy.                  

10:40.500 --> 10:41.200
                    REBECCA:    
                    I don't know

10:41.300 --> 10:42.500
                if I find       
                your come-ons   

10:42.500 --> 10:44.000
                disgusting or   
                merely pathetic.

10:44.000 --> 10:45.800
            I do know you're    
            giving me a headache

10:45.800 --> 10:47.000
                behind the eyes.

10:47.000 --> 10:49.900
                 It feels like  
                 a little insect

10:50.000 --> 10:52.300
        boring into my brain.   

10:54.000 --> 10:56.000
             Oh...!             

10:59.300 --> 11:00.400
    You didn't knock.           

11:00.400 --> 11:02.100
             Habit.             

11:02.100 --> 11:05.800
    Oh, my God.                 

11:05.800 --> 11:07.500
Boy, this place                 
doesn't even look               

11:07.500 --> 11:08.800
like my office anymore.         

